Schools\nEvent = DeclareSort(\"Event\")  # Events (school talent shows, high school dances)\nActivity = DeclareSort(\"Activity\")  # Activities (performing in school talent shows, chaperoning high school dances)\n\n# Define predicates\nAttends = Function(\"Attends\", Person, School, BoolSort())  # Attends(x, s)\nIs_Engaged = Function(\"Is_Engaged\", Person, School, BoolSort())  # Is_Engaged(x, s)\nIs_Inactive = Function(\"Is_Inactive\", Person, BoolSort())  # Is_Inactive(x)\nIs_Interested = Function(\"Is_Interested\", Person, BoolSort())  # Is_Interested(x)\nChaperones = Function(\"Chaperones\", Person, Event, BoolSort())  # Chaperones(x, e)\nIs_Student = Function(\"Is_Student\", Person, BoolSort())  # Is_Student(x)\nWishes_To_Further = Function(\"Wishes_To_Further\", Person, BoolSort())  # Wishes_To_Further(x)\nPerforms = Function(\"Performs\", Person, Activity, BoolSort())  # Performs(x, a)\n\n# Declare constants\nBonnie = Const(\"Bonnie\", Person)\nSchool_Attended = Const(\"School_Attended\", School)\nEvent_Attended = Const(\"Event_Attended\", Event)\nActivity_Performed = Const(\"Activity_Performed\", Activity)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ns = Const(\"s\", School)\ne = Const(\"e\", Event)\na = Const(\"a\", Activity)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(And(Performs(x, Activity_Performed), Attends(x, s)), Is_Engaged(x, s)))  # People in this club who perform in school talent shows often attend and are very engaged with school events.\nsolver.add(Or(ForAll([x], Implies(Performs(x, Activity_Performed), Is_Inactive(x))), Exists([x], And(Is_Inactive(x), Not(Is_Interested(x))))))  # (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Bonnie does not perform in school talent shows often. Schools (The school)\nEvent = DeclareSort(\"Event\")  # Events (Talent shows, dances)\nActivity = DeclareSort(\"Activity\")  # Activities (Performing, chaperoning)\n\n# Define predicates\nIsInClub = Function(\"IsInClub\", Person, BoolSort())  # AttendsSchool(x)\nIsEngagedWithSchool = Function(\"IsEngagedWithSchool\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsEngagedWithSchool(x)\nIsInactiveAndDisinterested = Function(\"IsInactiveAndDisinterested\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsInactiveAndDisinterested(x)\nChaperonesDance = Function(\"ChaperonesDance\", Person, BoolSort())  # ChaperonesDance(x)\nIsYoungChildOrTeenager = Function(\"IsYoungChildOrTeenager\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsYoungChildOrTeenager(x)\nWishesToFurtherAcademicCareer = Function(\"WishesToFurtherAcademicCareer\", Person, BoolSort())  # WishesToFurtherAcademicCareer(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nBonnie = Const(\"Bonnie\", Person)\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ny = Const(\"y\", Person)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Implies(IsInClub(Bonnie), And(Or(PerformsInSchoolTalentShow(Bonnie), Not(PerformsInSchoolTalentShow(Bonnie))))))  #         "conclusions": "If Bonnie either chaperones high school dances or, if she does not, she performs in school talent shows often, then Bonnie is both a young child or teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities and an inactive and disinterested member of the community.",
        "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nPerson = DeclareSort(\"Person\")  # People\nSchool = DeclareSort(\"School\")  # Schools\nEvent = DeclareSort(\"Event\")  # Events (e.g., talent shows, dances)\n\n# Define predicates\nIn_Club = Function(\"In_Club\", Person, BoolSort())  # In(x, Club)\nAttends_School = Function(\"Attends_School\", Person, School, BoolSort())  # Attends(x, School)\nIs_Student = Function(\"Is_Student\", Person, BoolSort())  # Student(x)\nIs_Active = Function(\"Is_Active\", Person, BoolSort())  # Active(x)\nIs_Interested = Function(\"Is_Interested\", Person, BoolSort())  # Interested(x)\nPerforms_Talent = Function(\"Performs_Talent\", Person, Event, BoolSort())  # Performs_Talent(x, Event)\nChaperones = Function(\"Chaperones\", Person, Event, BoolSort())  # Chaperones(x, Event)\nWishes_To_Further = Function(\"Wishes_To_Further\", Person, BoolSort())  # Wishes_To_Further(x)\nIs_Child = Function(\"Is_Child\", Person, BoolSort())  # Child(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nBonnie = Const(\"Bonnie\", Person)\nSchool_Bonnie_Attends = Const(\"School_Bonnie_Attends\", School)\nEvent_Bonnie_Performs = Const(\"Event_Bonnie_Performs\", Event)\nEvent_Bonnie_Chaperones = Const(\"Event_Bonnie_Chaperones\", Event)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ny = Const(\"y\", Person)\ns = Const(\"s\", School)\ne = Const(\"e\", Event)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(In_Club(x), And(Exists([e], And(Performs_Talent(x, e), Attends_School(x, s))))))  # People in this club who perform in school talent shows often attend and are very engaged with school events.\nsolver.add(Or(ForAll([x], Implies(In_Club(x), Exists([e], And(Performs_Talent(x, e))))), ForAll([x], Implies(In_Club(x), And(Not(Exists([e], And(Performs_Talent(x, e))), Not(Is_Active(x)))))))  # People in this club either perform in school talent shows often or are inactive and disinterested community members.\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(In_Club(x), Not(Is_Student(x))))  # People in this club who chaperone high school dances are not students who attend the school.\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(And(Not(Is_Active(x)), Not(Is_Interested(x))), Chaperones(x, e))))  # All people in this club who are inactive and disinterested members of their community chaperone high school dances.\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(And(Is_Child(x), In_Club(x), Wishes_To_Further(x)), Is_Student(x))))  # All young children and teenagers in this club who wish to further their academic careers and educational opportunities are students who attend the school.\nsolver.add(In_Club(Bonnie))  # Bonnie is in this club.\nsolver.add(Or(And(Attends_School(Bonnie, s), Is_Active(Bonnie)), Not(And(Attends_School(Bonnie, s), Is_Active(Bonnie))))  # Bonnie either attends and is very engaged with school events or is not someone who both attends and is very engaged with school events.\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Implies(Or(Chaperones(Bonnie, e), Not(Chaperones(Bonnie, e))), And(Wishes_To_Further(Bonnie), Not(Is_Active(Bonnie)))  # If Bonnie either chaperones high school dances or, if she does not, she performs in school talent shows often, then Bonnie is both a young child or teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities and an inactive and disinterested member of the community.\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: If Bonnie either chaperones high school dances or, if she does not, she performs in school talent shows often, then Bonnie is both a young child or teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities and an inactive and disinterested member of the community. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: If Bonnie either chaperones high school dances or, if she does not, she performs in school talent shows often, then Bonnie is both a young child or teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities and an inactive and disinterested member of the community. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\nprint(result)",

If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - Places (Company, Home, OtherCountries)\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Employee = Function(\"Is_Employee\", Person, BoolSort())  # Employee(x)\nIs_Manager = Function(\"Is_Manager\", Person, BoolSort())  # Manager(x)\nScheduled_Meeting = Function(\"Scheduled_Meeting\", Person, Person, BoolSort())  # ScheduledMeeting(x, y)\nIn_Company_Building = Function(\"In_Company_Building\", Person, BoolSort())  # InCompanyBuilding(x)\nAt_Home = Function(\"At_Home\", Person, BoolSort())  # AtHome(x)\nWorks_Remotely = Function(\"Works_Remotely\", Person, BoolSort())  # WorksRemotely(x)\nIn_Other_Countries = Function(\"In_Other_Countries\", Person, BoolSort())  # InOtherCountries(x)\nAppears_Today = Function(\"Appears_Today\", Person, BoolSort())  # AppearsToday(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nJames = Const(\"James\", Person)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ny = Const(\"y\", Person)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Scheduled_Meeting(x, y), In_Company_Building(x)))  # \u2200x \u2200y (ScheduledMeeting(x, y) \u2192 InCompanyBuilding(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(In_Company_Building(x), Exists([y], Scheduled_Meeting(x, y))))  # \u2200x (InCompanyBuilding(x) \u2192 \u2203y ScheduledMeeting(x, y))\nsolver.add(Or(In_Company_Building(x), At_Home(x)))  # \u2200x (InCompanyBuilding(x) \u2228 AtHome(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(At_Home(x), Works_Remotely(x))))  # \u2200x (AtHome(x) \u2192 WorksRemotely(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(In_Other_Countries(x), Works_Remotely(x))))  # \u2200x (InOtherCountries(x) \u2192 WorksRemotely(x))\nsolver.add(Not(Is_Manager(x)))  # \u00acManager(x)\nsolver.add(Implies(Appears_Today(James), Is_Manager(James)))  # AppearsToday(James) \u2192 Manager(James)\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Implies(Or(Is_Manager(James), In_Other_Countries(James)), Not(Or(At_Home(James), Works_Remotely(James))))  # (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat and result3 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: If James is either a manager or in other countries,  then James does not either has lunch at home or work remotely from home. **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Tom is not an Eastern wild turkey. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. Osceola(x)\nIs_Goulds = Function(\"Is_Goulds\", Person, BoolSort())  # Gould\u2019s(x)\nIs_Merrims = Function(\"Is_Merrims\", Person, BoolSort())  # Merriam\u2019s(x)\nIs_RioGrande = Function(\"Is_RioGrande\", Person, BoolSort())  # Joey(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nTom = Const(\"Tom\", Person)\nJoey = Const(\"Joey\", Person)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Not(Is_Eastern(Tom)))  # \u00acEastern(Tom)\nsolver.add(Not(Is_Osceola(Tom)))  # \u00acOsceola(Tom)\nsolver.add(Not(Is_Goulds(Tom)))  # \u00acGould\u2019s(Tom)\nsolver.add(Or(Not(Is_Merrims(Tom)), Not(Is_RioGrande(Tom))))  # Games (The Legend of Zelda, FIFA 22)\nRegion = DeclareSort(\"Region\")  # Regions (Japan, UK, etc.)\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Japanese = Function(\"Is_Japanese\", Company, BoolSort())  # Japanese(x)\nIs_Game = Function(\"Is_Game\", Game, BoolSort())  # Game(x)\nIs_In_Top10 = Function(\"Is_In_Top10\", Game, BoolSort())  # InTop10(x)\nSells_MillionPlus = Function(\"Sells_MillionPlus\", Game, BoolSort())  # SellsX(x)\nIs_MadeBy = Function(\"Is_MadeBy\", Company, Game, BoolSort())  # MadeBy(x, y)\n\n# Declare constants\nThe_Legend_Of_Zelda = Const(\"The_Legend_Of_Zelda\", Game)\nFIFA_22 = Const(\"FIFA_22\", Game)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Company)\ny = Const(\"y\", Game)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Is_Game(The_Legend_Of_Zelda))  # A Japanese game company created the game the Legend of Zelda.\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Japanese(x), Exists([y], And(Is_Game(y), Is_MadeBy(x, y))))))  # All games on the Top 10 list are made by Japanese game companies.\nsolver.add(ForAll([y], Implies(Sells_MillionPlus(y), Is_In_Top10(y))))  # FIFA 22 is made by a Japanese video game company.\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: FIFA 22 is made by a Japanese video game company. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: FIFA 22 is not made by a Japanese video game company. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(result)",

Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - Games\nList = DeclareSort(\"List\")  # Lists (Top 10 list)\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Japanese = Function(\"Is_Japanese\", GameCompany, BoolSort())  # Japanese(x)\nCreated = Function(\"Created\", GameCompany, Game, BoolSort())  # Created(x, y)\nIs_In_List = Function(\"Is_In_List\", Game, List, BoolSort())  # InList(x, y)\nSellsMoreThanOneMillion = Function(\"SellsMoreThanOneMillion\", Game, BoolSort())  # SellsMoreThanOneMillion(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nThe_Legend_Of_Zelda = Const(\"The_Legend_Of_Zelda\", Game)\nA_Japanese_Game_Company = Const(\"A_Japanese_Game_Company\", GameCompany)\nThe_Top_10_List = Const(\"The_Top_10_List\", List)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Game)\ny = Const(\"y\", GameCompany)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Is_Japanese(A_Japanese_Game_Company))  # A Japanese game company exists\nsolver.add(Created(A_Japanese_Game_Company, The_Legend_Of_Zelda))  # The Legend of Zelda was created by a Japanese game company\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(SellsMoreThanOneMillion(x), Is_In_List(x, The_Top_10_List))))  # The Legend of Zelda is not in the Top 10 list\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: The Legend of Zelda is not on the Top 10 list. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: The Legend of Zelda is on the Top 10 list. Places (Campus)\n\n# Define predicates\nIsCute = Function(\"IsCute\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Cute(x)\nIsTurtle = Function(\"IsTurtle\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Turtle(x)\nIsSquirrel = Function(\"IsSquirrel\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Squirrel(x)\nIsSkittish = Function(\"IsSkittish\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Skittish(x)\nIsCalm = Function(\"IsCalm\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Calm(x)\nIsSpottedNearCampus = Function(\"IsSpottedNearCampus\", Animal, BoolSort())  # SpottedNearCampus(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nRockie = Const(\"Rockie\", Animal)\nx = Const(\"x\", Animal)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsSpottedNearCampus(x), IsCute(x)))  # \u2200x (SpottedNearCampus(x) \u2192 Cute(x))\nsolver.add(Exists([x], And(IsSpottedNearCampus(x), IsTurtle(x)))  # \u2203x (SpottedNearCampus(x) \u2227 Turtle(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsSpottedNearCampus(x), Or(IsRabbit(x), IsSquirrel(x))))  # (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Rockie is a turtle.         "conclusions": "If Rockie is cute and calm, then Rockie is a skittish turtle.",
        "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nAnimal = DeclareSort(\"Animal\")  # Animals (Rabbits, Turtles, Squirrels)\nLocation = DeclareSort(\"Location\")  # Locations (Campus)\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_SpottedNearCampus = Function(\"Is_SpottedNearCampus\", Animal, Location, BoolSort())  # SpottedNear(C, x)\nIs_Cute = Function(\"Is_Cute\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Cute(x)\nIs_Skittish = Function(\"Is_Skittish\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Skittish(x)\nIs_Calm = Function(\"Is_Calm\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Calm(x)\nIs_Rabbit = Function(\"Is_Rabbit\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Rabbit(x)\nIs_Turtle = Function(\"Is_Turtle\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Turtle(x)\nIs_Squirrel = Function(\"Is_Squirrel\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Squirrel(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nRockie = Const(\"Rockie\", Animal)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Animal)\ny = Const(\"y\", Location)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_SpottedNearCampus(x, y), Is_Cute(x)))  # \u2200x (SpottedNear(x, y) \u2192 Cute(x))\nsolver.add(Exists([x], And(Is_SpottedNearCampus(x, y), Is_Turtle(x)))  # \u2203x (SpottedNear(x, y) \u2227 Turtle(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_SpottedNearCampus(x, y), Or(Is_Rabbit(x), Is_Squirrel(x))))  # \u2200x (SpottedNear(x, y) \u2192 Rabbit(x) \u2228 Squirrel(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Skittish(x), Not(Is_Calm(x))))  # \u2200x (Skittish(x) \u2192 \u00acCalm(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_SpottedNearCampus(x, y), Is_Skittish(x)))  # \u2200x (SpottedNear(x, y) \u2192 Skittish(x))\nsolver.add(Is_SpottedNearCampus(Rockie, y))  # SpottedNear(Rockie, y)\nsolver.add(Is_Calm(Rockie))  # Calm(Rockie)\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Implies(Is_Cute(Rockie), Is_Skittish(Rockie))  # Cute(Rockie) \u2192 Skittish(Rockie)\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: If Rockie is cute and calm, then Rockie is a skittish turtle. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: If Rockie is cute and calm, then Rockie is not a skittish turtle. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(result)",

Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - BingeWatched(x: Person, y: Show)\nIs_Downloaded = Function(\"Is_Downloaded\", Person, Show, BoolSort())  # Downloaded(x: Person, y: Show)\nIs_Shared = Function(\"Is_Shared\", Person, Show, BoolSort())  # Shared(x: Person, y: Show)\n\n# Declare constants\nStranger_Things = Const(\"Stranger_Things\", Show)\nBlack_Mirror = Const(\"Black_Mirror\", Show)\nKaren = Const(\"Karen\", Person)\nLisa = Const(\"Lisa\", Person)\n\n# Define variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Show)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Is_Popular(Stranger_Things))  # Stranger Things is a popular Netflix show\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_Popular(x), Is_BingeWatched(Karen, x)))  # If a Netflix show is popular, Karen will binge-watch it\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_BingeWatched(Karen, x), Is_Downloaded(Karen, x))))  # If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Planet\nAttribute = DeclareSort(\"Attribute\")  # Attribute\n\n# Define predicates\nIsAlien = Function(\"IsAlien\", Person, BoolSort())  # Alien(x)\nIsExtraterrestrial = Function(\"IsExtraterrestrial\", Person, BoolSort())  # Extraterrestrial(x)\nIsFrom = Function(\"IsFrom\", Person, Planet, BoolSort())  # From(x, y)\nIsHuman = Function(\"IsHuman\", Person, BoolSort())  # Human(x)\nIsIntelligent = Function(\"IsIntelligent\", Person, BoolSort())  # Intelligent(x)\nIsMars = Function(\"IsMars\", Planet, BoolSort())  # Mars(y)\nIsEarth = Function(\"IsEarth\", Planet, BoolSort())  # Earth(y)\n\n# Declare constants\nMarvin = Const(\"Marvin\", Person)\nMars = Const(\"Mars\", Planet)\nEarth = Const(\"Earth\", Planet)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ny = Const(\"y\", Planet)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsAlien(x), IsExtraterrestrial(x)))  # All aliens are extraterrestrials.\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsFrom(x, Mars), IsAlien(x))))  # If someone is from Mars, then they are an alien.\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Not(IsExtraterrestrial(x)), Not(IsHuman(x))))  # No extraterrestrials are human.\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsIntelligent(x), IsHuman(x))))  # All highly intelligent beings from Earth are humans.\nsolver.add(IsIntelligent(Marvin))  # Marvin is a highly intelligent being.\nsolver.add(Or(IsFrom(Marvin, Earth), Not(IsFrom(Marvin, Earth))))  # Marvin is either from Earth and from Mars, or he is from neither.\nsolver.add(Implies(Not(IsFrom(Marvin, Earth)), IsExtraterrestrial(Marvin)))  # If Marvin is not from Earth, then Marvin is an extraterrestrial.\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Not(Or(IsHuman(Marvin), IsFrom(Marvin, Mars)))  # Marvin is neither a human nor from Mars.\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Marvin is neither a human nor from Mars. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Marvin is either a human or from Mars. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(result)",

**Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - Professional wrestling stables (Diamond Mine, Imperium)\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_LedBy = Function(\"Is_LedBy\", Person, Stable, BoolSort())  # LedBy(x, s)\nIs_Member = Function(\"Is_Member\", Person, Stable, BoolSort())  # Member(x, s)\nHas_Feud = Function(\"Has_Feud\", Stable, Stable, BoolSort())  # Feud(s1, s2)\n\n# Declare constants\nRoderick_Strong = Const(\"Roderick_Strong\", Person)\nCreed_Brothers = Const(\"Creed_Brothers\", Stable)\nIvy_Nile = Const(\"Ivy_Nile\", Person)\nImperium = Const(\"Imperium\", Stable)\nDiamond_Mine = Const(\"Diamond_Mine\", Stable)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ny = Const(\"y\", Person)\nz = Const(\"z\", Stable)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Is_LedBy(Roderick_Strong, Diamond_Mine))  # Roderick Strong leads Diamond Mine\nsolver.add(Is_Member(Creed_Brothers, Diamond_Mine))  # Creed Brothers are members of Diamond Mine\nsolver.add(Is_Member(Ivy_Nile, Diamond_Mine))  # Ivy Nile is a member of Diamond Mine\nsolver.add(Has_Feud(Diamond_Mine, Imperium))  # Diamond Mine has a feud with Imperium\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Not(Has_Feud(Imperium, Ivy_Nile))  # Imperium does not have a feud with Ivy Nile\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(Is_Member(Ivy_Nile, Diamond_Mine)))  # Negate a premise and check for contradiction\nsolver.add(Not(Has_Feud(Diamond_Mine, Imperium)))  # Negate a premise and check for contradiction\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult4 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Imperium does not have a feud with Ivy Nile. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Imperium has a feud with Ivy Nile. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. LedBy(x, y)\nIs_Composer = Function(\"Is_Composer\", Person, BoolSort())  # Composer(x)\nIs_Conductor = Function(\"Is_Conductor\", Person, BoolSort())  # Conductor(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nBeethoven = Const(\"Beethoven\", Person)\nSymphony_No_9 = Const(\"Symphony_No_9\", MusicPiece)\nVienna_Music_Society = Const(\"Vienna_Music_Society\", Organization)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ny = Const(\"y\", MusicPiece)\nz = Const(\"z\", Organization)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Wrote(Beethoven, Symphony_No_9))  # Beethoven wrote Symphony No. 9\nsolver.add(Premiered(Vienna_Music_Society, Symphony_No_9))  # Vienna Music Society premiered Symphony No. 9\nsolver.add(Is_Orchestra(Vienna_Music_Society))  # Vienna Music Society is an orchestra\nsolver.add(Is_LedBy(Vienna_Music_Society, Beethoven))  # Vienna Music Society is led by Beethoven\nsolver.add(Or(Is_Composer(x), Is_Conductor(x)))  # x is either a composer or a conductor\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Not(Is_Conductor(Beethoven))  # Beethoven is not a conductor\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Beethoven is not a conductor. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Beethoven is a conductor. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(result)",

Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - Evocative(x)\nIs_Dreamy = Function(\"Is_Dreamy\", Building, BoolSort())  # Dreamy(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nMax = Const(\"Max\", Person)\nZaha_Hadid = Const(\"Zaha_Hadid\", Person)\nKelly_Wearstler = Const(\"Kelly_Wearstler\", Person)\ndesign_by_Max = Const(\"design_by_Max\", Building)\nx = Const(\"x\", Style)\ny = Const(\"y\", Building)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Zaha_Hadid_Style(x), Has_Interesting_Geometries(y)))  # \u2200x (Zaha_HadidDesignStyle(x) \u2192 \u2200y Adores(Max, x) \u2192 InterestingGeometries(y))\nsolver.add(Not(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Brutalist_Building(x), Has_Interesting_Geometries(x))))  # \u00ac\u2200x (BrutalistBuilding(x) \u2192 InterestingGeometries(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Or(Is_Zaha_Hadid_Design_Style(x), Is_Kelly_Wearstler_Design_Style(x))))  # \u2200x (Zaha_HadidDesignStyle(x) \u2228 KellyWearstlerDesignStyle(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Kelly_Wearstler_Design_Style(x), Is_Evocative(y))))  # \u2200x (KellyWearstlerDesignStyle(x) \u2192 Evocative(y))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Kelly_Wearstler_Design_Style(x), Is_Dreamy(y))))  # \u2200x (KellyWearstlerDesignStyle(x) \u2192 Dreamy(y))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(And(Adores(Max, x), Has_Interesting_Geometries(x)), And(Is_Brutalist_Building(x), Is_Evocative(x))))  # \u2200x (Adores(Max, x) \u2227 InterestingGeometries(x) \u2192 BrutalistBuilding(x) \u2227 Evocative(x))\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Exists([x], Or(Is_Evocative(x), Is_Dreamy(x)))  # \u2203x (Evocative(x) \u2228 Dreamy(x))\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: A design by Max is either evocative or dreamy. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: A design by Max is neither evocative nor dreamy. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(result)",

Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - ActiveInMajorTennis(x)\nLostTo = Function(\"LostTo\", Person, Person, BoolSort())  # LostTo(x, y)\nIsFemale = Function(\"IsFemale\", Person, BoolSort())  # Female(x)\nIsMale = Function(\"IsMale\", Person, BoolSort())  # LostTo(x, y, t)\nIs_Active_In_Major_Tennis = Function(\"Is_Active_In_Major_Tennis\", Person, BoolSort())  # ActiveInMajorTennis(x)\nIs_Female = Function(\"Is_Female\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsFemale(x)\nIs_Male = Function(\"Is_Male\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsMale(x)\nIs_At = Function(\"Is_At\", Person, Tournament, BoolSort())  # At(x, t)\nIs_Lost_To_RN = Function(\"Is_Lost_To_RN\", Person, Tournament, BoolSort())  # LostToRN(x, t)\n\n# Declare constants\nIga_Swi\u0105tek = Const(\"Iga_Swi\u0105tek\", Person)\nCoco_Gauff = Const(\"Coco_Gauff\", Person)\nRafael_Nadal = Const(\"Rafael_Nadal\", Person)\nRoland_Garros_2022 = Const(\"Roland_Garros_2022\", Tournament)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ny = Const(\"y\", Person)\nt = Const(\"t\", Tournament)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Implies(Ranked_Highly_By_WTA(x), Is_Active_In_Major_Tennis(x)))  # If someone is ranked highly by the Women's Tennis Association, then they are one of the most active players in major tennis.\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Lost_To(x, Iga_Swi\u0105tek, Roland_Garros_2022), Ranked_Highly_By_WTA(x))))  # Everyone who lost to Iga \u015awi\u0105tek at Roland Garros 2022 is ranked highly by the Women's Tennis Association.\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_At(x, Roland_Garros_2022), Lost_To(x, Iga_Swi\u0105tek, Roland_Garros_2022))))  # All female tennis players at Roland Garros 2022 lost to Iga \u015awi\u0105tek.\nsolver.add(Or(Is_Female(x), Is_Male(x)))  # All tennis players at Roland Garros 2022 are either female or male.\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Male(x), Lost_To(x, Rafael_Nadal, Roland_Garros_2022)))  # All male tennis players at Roland Garros in 2022 lost to Rafael Nadal.\nsolver.add(Or(Ranked_Highly_By_WTA(Coco_Gauff), Lost_To(Coco_Gauff, Rafael_Nadal, Roland_Garros_2022), Not(Is_Male(Coco_Gauff))))  # If Coco Gauff is ranked highly by the Women's Tennis Association or lost to Rafael Nadal, then Coco Gauff is not a male tennis player at Roland Garros 2022.\nsolver.add(Is_At(Coco_Gauff, Roland_Garros_2022))  # Coco Gauff is at Roland Garros 2022.\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Not(And(Lost_To(Coco_Gauff, Iga_Swi\u0105tek, Roland_Garros_2022), Is_Active_In_Major_Tennis(Coco_Gauff)))  # Coco Gauff is not both a player who lost to Iga \u015awi\u0105tek at Roland Garros 2022 and one of the most active players in major tennis.\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Coco Gauff is not both a player who lost to Iga \u015awi\u0105tek at Roland Garros 2022 and one of the most active players in major tennis. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Coco Gauff is both a player who lost to Iga \u015awi\u0105tek at Roland Garros 2022 and one of the most active players in major tennis. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\nprint(result)",

Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Some pets are cats. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(result)",

Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - The Python Code should be enclosed within <PYTHON> and </PYTHON>.\n\nYou need to understand the aformentioned rules before generating the codes.\n\n\nThe following is the problem you need to solve.\n\n<Premises>\nThere are four seasons in a year: Spring, Summer, Fall, and Winter.\nAll students who want to have a long vacation have summer as their favorite season.\nEmma's favorite season is summer.\nMia's favorite season is not the same as Emma's. \nJames wants to have a long vacation.\n</Premises>\n<Conclusion>\nMia's favorite season is spring.\n</Conclusion>\n<PYTHON>\n"

(True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: 1984 is not printed text. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - LanguageFamily\nCountry = DeclareSort(\"Country\")  # Country\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Romance = Function(\"Is_Romance\", Language, BoolSort())  # Romance(x: Language)\nIs_IndoEuropean = Function(\"Is_IndoEuropean\", Language, BoolSort())  # IndoEuropean(x: Language)\nIs_Related = Function(\"Is_Related\", Language, Language, BoolSort())  # Related(x: Language, y: Language)\nIs_Member = Function(\"Is_Member\", Family, Language, BoolSort())  # (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: German is not a Romance language.         "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nPerson = DeclareSort(\"Person\")  # People (Robert Lewandowski, other soccer players)\nTeam = DeclareSort(\"Team\")  # Teams (Bayern Munchen)\n\n# Define predicates\nIsStriker = Function(\"IsStriker\", Person, BoolSort())  # Striker(x)\nIsSoccerPlayer = Function(\"IsSoccerPlayer\", Person, BoolSort())  # SoccerPlayer(x)\nPlayedFor = Function(\"PlayedFor\", Person, Team, BoolSort())  # PlayedFor(x, team)\nLeft = Function(\"Left\", Person, Team, BoolSort())  # Left(x, team)\n\n# Declare constants\nRobert_Lewandowski = Const(\"Robert_Lewandowski\", Person)\nBayern_Munchen = Const(\"Bayern_Munchen\", Team)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Team)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(IsStriker(Robert_Lewandowski))  # Robert Lewandowski is a striker\nsolver.add(IsSoccerPlayer(Robert_Lewandowski))  # Robert Lewandowski is a soccer player\nsolver.add(Left(Robert_Lewandowski, Bayern_Munchen))  # Robert Lewandowski left Bayern Munchen\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Left(Robert_Lewandowski, x), Not(PlayedFor(Robert_Lewandowski, x))))  # If Robert Lewandowski left a team, he no longer plays for that team\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = PlayedFor(Robert_Lewandowski, Bayern_Munchen)  # Robert Lewandowski plays for Bayern Munchen\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Robert Lewandowski plays for Bayern Munchen. Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     -         "conclusions": "Montana is home to the city of Missoula.",
        "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nCity = DeclareSort(\"City\")  # Cities (Billings, Butte, Helena, Missoula, StPierre, WhiteSulphurSprings)\nState = DeclareSort(\"State\")  # States (Montana)\n\n# Define predicates\nInState = Function(\"InState\", City, State, BoolSort())  # InState(x, s)\nIsInUS = Function(\"IsInUS\", City, BoolSort())  # isInUS(x)\nIsCapital = Function(\"IsCapital\", City, BoolSort())  # IsCapital(x)\nIsIn = Function(\"In\", City, City, BoolSort())  # In(x, y)\n\n# Declare constants\nBillings = Const(\"Billings\", City)\nButte = Const(\"Butte\", City)\nHelena = Const(\"Helena\", City)\nMissoula = Const(\"Missoula\", City)\nStPierre = Const(\"StPierre\", City)\nWhiteSulphurSprings = Const(\"WhiteSulphurSprings\", City)\nMontana = Const(\"Montana\", State)\nUS = Const(\"US\", State)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", City)\ny = Const(\"y\", City)\ns = Const(\"s\", State)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(InState(Billings, Montana))  # Billings is a city in the state of Montana\nsolver.add(InState(Butte, Montana))  # The state of Montana includes the cities of Butte\nsolver.add(InState(Helena, Montana))  # The state of Montana includes the cities of Helena\nsolver.add(InState(Missoula, Montana))  # The state of Montana includes the cities of Missoula\nsolver.add(InState(Butte, US))  # White Sulphur Springs and Butte are cities in the same state in U.S.\nsolver.add(InState(WhiteSulphurSprings, US))  # White Sulphur Springs and Butte are cities in the same state in U.S.\nsolver.add(Not(InState(StPierre, Montana)))  # The city of St Pierre is not in the state of Montana\nsolver.add(Not(In(Butte, StPierre)))  # Any city in Butte is not in St Pierre\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsInUS(x), Exists([y], And(InState(x, y), y != x))))  # A city can only be in one state in U.S. except for Bristol, Texarkana, Texhoma and Union City\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = InState(Missoula, Montana)  # Montana is home to the city of Missoula\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Montana is home to the city of Missoula. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Montana is not home to the city of Missoula. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(result)",

Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     -         "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nAnimal = DeclareSort(\"Animal\")  # Animals (Cows, Alligators, Pets)\nDomesticated_Animal = DeclareSort(\"Domesticated_Animal\")  # Domesticated Animals\nBrown_Swiss_Cattle = DeclareSort(\"Brown_Swiss_Cattle\")  # Brown Swiss Cattle\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Brown_Swiss = Function(\"Is_Brown_Swiss\", Animal, BoolSort())  # BrownSwiss(x)\nIs_Cow = Function(\"Is_Cow\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Cow(x)\nIs_Pet = Function(\"Is_Pet\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Pet(x)\nIs_Domesticated = Function(\"Is_Domesticated\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Domesticated(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nTed = Const(\"Ted\", Animal)\nx = Const(\"x\", Animal)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Brown_Swiss(x), Is_Cow(x)))  # \u2200x (BrownSwiss(x) \u2192 Cow(x))\nsolver.add(Exists([x], And(Is_Pet(x), Is_Brown_Swiss(x)))  # \u2203x (Pet(x) \u2227 BrownSwiss(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Cow(x), Is_Domesticated(x))))  # \u2200x (Cow(x) \u2192 Domesticated(x))\nsolver.add(Not(Is_Domesticated(Ted)))  # \u00acDomesticated(Ted)\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = And(Is_Pet(Ted), Is_Brown_Swiss(Ted))  # Pet(Ted) \u2227 BrownSwiss(Ted)\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Ted is a pet and Brown Swiss cattle. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Ted is not a pet and not Brown Swiss cattle. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(result)",

Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Residential colleges within a university\nYear = DeclareSort(\"Year\")  # Years\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Private = Function(\"Is_Private\", University, BoolSort())  # Private(x)\nIs_Ivy_League = Function(\"Is_Ivy_League\", University, BoolSort())  # IvyLeague(x)\nIs_Research = Function(\"Is_Research\", University, BoolSort())  # Research(x)\nMovedTo = Function(\"MovedTo\", University, University, Year, BoolSort())  # Moved(x, y, t)\nHasEndowment = Function(\"HasEndowment\", University, BoolSort())  # HasEndowment(x)\nHasLargestEndowment = Function(\"HasLargestEndowment\", University, University, BoolSort())  # LargestEndowment(x, y)\nLocatedIn = Function(\"LocatedIn\", University, University, BoolSort())  # LocatedIn(x, y)\nIsListed = Function(\"IsListed\", University, BoolSort())  # Listed(x)\nIsResidential = Function(\"IsResidential\", College, BoolSort())  # Residential(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nYale = Const(\"Yale\", University)\nNewHaven = Const(\"NewHaven\", University)\nYear_1716 = Const(\"Year_1716\", Year)\nx = Const(\"x\", University)\ny = Const(\"y\", University)\nz = Const(\"z\", College)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Is_Private(Yale))  # Yale is a private university\nsolver.add(Is_Ivy_League(Yale))  # Yale is an Ivy League university\nsolver.add(Is_Research(Yale))  # Yale is a research university\nsolver.add(MovedTo(Yale, NewHaven, Year_1716))  # Yale moved to New Haven in 1716\nsolver.add(HasEndowment(Yale))  # Yale has an endowment\nsolver.add(IsListed(Yale))  # Yale is listed\nsolver.add(IsResidential(z))  # z is a residential college\nsolver.add(IsListed(z))  # (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     -         "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nStock = DeclareSort(\"Stock\")  # Stocks (growth or mature)\nFund = DeclareSort(\"Fund\")  # Funds (retirement or other)\n\n# Define predicates\nIsGrowthStock = Function(\"IsGrowthStock\", Stock, BoolSort())  # GrowthStock(x)\nIsBoughtForProfits = Function(\"IsBoughtForProfits\", Stock, BoolSort())  # BoughtForProfits(x)\nIsSuitableForRetirement = Function(\"IsSuitableForRetirement\", Stock, BoolSort())  # SuitableForRetirement(x)\nIsKO = Function(\"IsKO\", Stock, BoolSort())  # KO(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nx = Const(\"x\", Stock)\ny = Const(\"y\", Stock)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsGrowthStock(x), IsBoughtForProfits(x)))  # \u2200x (GrowthStock(x) \u2192 BoughtForProfits(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsBoughtForProfits(x), Not(IsSuitableForRetirement(x))))  # \u2200x (BoughtForProfits(x) \u2192 \u00acSuitableForRetirement(x))\nsolver.add(Exists([x], And(IsGrowthStock(x), x != y))  # \u2203x GrowthStock(x)\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsMature(x), IsSuitableForRetirement(x))))  # \u2200x (Mature(x) \u2192 SuitableForRetirement(x))\nsolver.add(IsMature(KO))  # Mature(KO)\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = IsStock(KO)  # KO is a stock\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: KO is a stock. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: KO is not a stock. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(result)",
